04367nam a22006135i 9780822374404DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20162016ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015032647  a97808223744047 a10.1515/97808223744042doi  a(DE-B1597)554113  a(OCoLC)944187042  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aHN310.P33bO85 2016 4aHN310.P33bO85 2016 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a303.48/4098611 aOslender, Ulrich, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Geographies of Social Movements :bAfro-Colombian Mobilization and the Aquatic Space /cUlrich Oslender. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b23 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Ecologies for the Twenty-First Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue: Black Communities in Colombia and the Constitution of 1991 -- tIntroduction: The Geographies of Social Movements -- t1. Toward a Critical Place Perspective on Social Movements -- tInterlude: Meeting Don Agapito: Reflections on Fieldwork -- t2. Mapping Meandering Poetics and an Aquatic Sense of Place: Oral Tradition as Hidden Transcript of Resistance -- t3. Historical Geographies of Resistance and Convivencia in the Pacific Lowlands -- t4. Mobilizing the Aquatic Space: The Forming of Community Councils -- t5. Ideals, Practices, and Leadership of the Community Councils -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Geographies of Social Movements Ulrich Oslender proposes a critical place perspective to examine the activism of black communities in the lowland rain forest of Colombia's Pacific Coast region. Drawing on extensive ethnographic fieldwork in and around the town of Guapi, Oslender examines how the work of local community councils, which have organized around newly granted ethnic and land rights since the early 1990s, is anchored to space and place. Exploring how residents' social relationships are entangled with the region's rivers, streams, swamps, rain, and tides, Oslender argues that this "aquatic space"-his conceptualization of the mutually constitutive relationships between people and their rain forest environment-provides a local epistemology that has shaped the political process. Oslender demonstrates that social mobilization among Colombia's Pacific Coast black communities is best understood as emerging out of their place-based identity and environmental imaginaries. He argues that the critical place perspective proposed accounts more fully for the multiple, multiscalar, rooted, and networked experiences within social movements.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aBlacks - Political activity - Colombia - Pacific Coast. 0aBlacksxLand tenurezColombiazPacific Coast. 0aBlacksxPolitical activityzColombiazPacific Coast. 0aLand reformzColombia. 0aSocial movementszColombiazPacific Coast. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374404zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374404.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles